    "articulo-registro": {
        title: "How to register when arriving in Switzerland (Inhabitants Control)",
        description: "Step-by-step guide on registering in your new commune (Contrôle des habitants) after moving to Switzerland. Deadlines, documents and what happens next.",
        keywords: "Swiss commune registration, Swiss registration, control of inhabitants, living in Switzerland, first month in Switzerland",
        keywordsLocalized: true,
        category: "Formalities and Permits",
        hub: "tramites",
        slug: "registering-in-switzerland-commune",
        readingTime: 5,
        summary: "If you move to Switzerland to reside, you usually have to register with your commune within a few days (often 14). Proof of registration usually allows you to start working and advance procedures while the permit card arrives.",
        featuredImage: "media/guides/registrarse-en-suiza.jpg",
        imageAlt: "Person arriving at the Swiss Rathaus (town hall) to register with their suitcase",
        content: `<div class="article-content">
                <h2>Introduction</h2>
                <p>The <strong>registration in the commune</strong> (Inhabitant Control / <i>Contrôle des habitants</i> / <i>Einwohnerkontrolle</i>) is the procedure that <strong> formalizes your residence</strong> in Switzerland. It is key to activate the administrative circuit: permit, health insurance, taxes, school, etc.</p>
                <p>Important: <strong>not everyone who "enters Switzerland" registers</strong>. This article is aimed at people who <strong>move to live</strong> (for work, studies or family reasons) and need an official address.</p>

                <h2>How the system works</h2>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>You choose your commune</strong> (your real address) and locate the registry office.</li>
                    <li><strong>Make an appointment</strong> if applicable (very common in large cities).</li>
                    <li><strong>You present documents</strong>, pay a fee and declare your address.</li>
                    <li>The commune gives you a <strong>registration certificate/certificate</strong> (according to canton and situation).</li>
                    <li>The file is sent to the <strong>cantonal migration authority</strong> and the <strong>permission card</strong> arrives by mail (weeks).</li>
                </ol>
                <div class="callout warning">
                    <strong>Deadlines:</strong> in many cantons registration must be done in <strong>14 days</strong> (sometimes less) and, if you come to work, normally <strong>before the first day</strong>. The details change by canton and commune: always confirm on the official website of your municipality.
                </div>

                <h2>Requirements and rules</h2>
                <h3>1) Who should register (and who should not)?</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>HTMLTAG_59___Tourist / short stay (e.g. up to 90 days):</strong> normally <strong>no communal registration</strong> as a resident.</li>
                    <li>HTMLTAG_65___You move to live (work, studies, family):</strong> in practice <strong>yes</strong>, you must register in your commune within the local deadline.</li>
                    <li><strong>EU/EFTA job search engine:</strong> you can spend some time searching (with specific rules). If you settle and/or exceed the permitted period without permission, <strong>you must regularize</strong> your situation according to the canton.</li>
                    <li><strong>Frontier (G Permit):</strong> you work in Switzerland but <strong>you live outside</strong>. It is not processed like a "normal" residence registration. Even so, there are procedures with the canton/employer and tax/insurance requirements.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>If your case is mixed (e.g., you start as a short stay and then they hire you), the rule of thumb is: <strong>as soon as you have a reason for residence and domicile, act quickly</strong> to avoid delays or penalties.</p>

                <h3>2) Address and accommodation: yes, it can be temporary</h3>
                <p>If you are in a hotel, Airbnb, or someone's home when you arrive, in many cases you can register at a <strong>temporary address</strong> and update it later. If you are staying in a private home, a <strong>accommodation certificate</strong> signed by the person holding the rental is usually requested.</p>

                <h3>3) Common documents</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Identity document (DNI/passport).</li>
                    <li><strong>Reason for stay:</strong> employment contract, admission to studies, or documentation of own resources (depending on the situation).</li>
                    <li>Rental contract or accommodation certificate.</li>
                    <li>Passport photo (or they take it there, depending on the commune).</li>
                    <li>Family documentation if applicable (marriage, birth of children, etc.).</li>
                </ul>
                <p>It is also common to pay an <strong>administrative fee</strong>. The range depends on the canton and the type of permit.</p>

                <h2>Concrete examples</h2>
                <h3>Example 1 — You arrive with a job and temporary accommodation</h3>
                <p>You register with your contract + document + temporary address. You get a receipt and you can advance bank/insurance while the permit card arrives. When you sign the definitive rental, you make the change of address.</p>

                <h3>Example 2 — You arrive as a student</h3>
                <p>You present admission/registration and proof of means/coverage according to the canton. Registration activates the rest of the procedures (insurance, taxes if you work, etc.).</p>

                <h3>Example 3 — You are from the border</h3>
                <p>You do not follow the same circuit as a resident. Your leave and obligations are usually managed with the employer and cantonal authority, with specific tax/insurance rules. Don't treat him like "a B living abroad".</p>

                <h2>Common errors</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Confusing entry with residence:</strong> visiting Switzerland does not imply registration; move yes.</li>
                    <li><strong>Wait until you have a final apartment</strong> and miss the deadline.</li>
                    <li><strong>Do not make an appointment</strong> on time in communities with a saturated agenda.</li>
                    <li><strong>Do not update the address</strong> when you move (changes and deregistrations/registrations matter a lot in Switzerland).</li>
                    <li><strong>Do not prepare family documents</strong> in advance (apostille/translations where appropriate).</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Practical Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Search for the official website of your commune and check "Anmeldung / Contrôle des habitants / Einwohnerkontrolle".</li>
                    <li>Prepare a PDF with documents + printed copies.</li>
                    <li>If your situation does not fit (no contract, border, regrouping), ask in writing for the exact list of requirements.</li>
                    <li>After registration, prioritize: <a href="#/seguro-medico-lamal-suiza">medical insurance (LAMal)</a> and bank account.</li>
                    <li>For the "first month", use: <a href="#/tramites-llegada-suiza">Procedure checklist</a>.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Official sources</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><a href="https://www.ch.ch/es/entrar-y-vivir-en-suiza/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ch.ch — Enter and live in Switzerland</a></li>
                    <li><a href="https://www.sem.admin.ch/sem/es/home/themen/aufenthalt.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SEM — Residence / Aufenthalt</a></li>
                    <li>Official website of your commune (Inhabitant Control / Einwohnerkontrolle).</li>
                </ul>
            </div>`
    },
