        supportingImages: [],
        content: `<div class="article-content">
                <h2>Introduction</h2>
                <p>Switzerland is one of the countries with the highest cost of living in Europe, and that is why organizing every franc is key. Financial planning allows you to avoid surprises, control expenses and calmly decide about housing, food and taxes. The Swiss Budget Advisory Service (Conseil Budgetaire) publishes real examples that help to make reference in daily life.</p>

                <h2>Budget for a single person</h2>
                <p>Living alone requires balancing fixed expenses with monthly net income.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Rent:</strong> a studio or one-bedroom apartment usually costs between 1,400 and 2,200 CHF including charges. Plan annual increases and share expenses when possible.</li>
                    <li><strong>Food:</strong> preparing food at home in chains such as Migros or Coop keeps the expense between 400 and 500 CHF; eating out doubles the game.</li>
                    <li><strong>Transport:</strong> the urban monthly pass is around 80-140 CHF; Those under 25 years of age or those who live nearby can opt for more affordable options.</li>
                    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> the LAMal basic premium ranges from 300 to 450 CHF (depending on canton and age); defines the deductible and separates a fund to cover co-payments.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Budget for couples without children</h2>
                <p>Two adults share expenses but also reserve space for leisure and the future.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Housing:</strong> a 2-3 room apartment costs CHF 2,300-3,200; They distribute electricity, internet and maintenance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Leisure:</strong> restaurants, gym and getaways represent 200-400 CHF; Set a monthly limit so as not to sacrifice savings.</li>
                    <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> in addition to LAMal, they add civil liability and home, especially if they have pets or a car.</li>
                    <li><strong>Savings:</strong> set aside at least 10-15% of income for emergencies or goals (same recommendation as Swiss budget advisors).</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Budget for families with children</h2>
                <p>Families face items that multiply with each child.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Daycare:</strong> a place costs between CHF 1,200 and CHF 2,000 per child, although cantonal subsidies can reduce the amount.</li>
                    <li><strong>Education:</strong> Materials, excursions and language courses add up to CHF 100-200 per month per child.</li>
                    <li><strong>Food:</strong> preparing family menus raises the amount to 700-900 CHF per month.</li>
                    <li><strong>Clothes:</strong> plan renewals and discounts to avoid exaggerating spending.</li>
                    <li><strong>Transport:</strong> family passes or school trips add 150-250 CHF.</li>
                    <li><strong>Extracurricular activities:</strong> music, sport or tutoring can cost CHF 100-250 per child each month.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Family with 1 child</h3>
                <p>A typical example combines a rent of CHF 2,400, partial daycare of CHF 1,000 and food around CHF 650. Sharing transfers helps reduce transportation spending.</p>
                <h3>Family with 2 children</h3>
                <p>Day care and extracurricular activities double; It is advisable to prioritize public options or centers with tiered prices per sibling.</p>
                <h3>Family with 3 children</h3>
                <p>The focus should be efficiency: cheaper energy and transportation, a contingency fund, and taking advantage of free public schooling.</p>

                <h2>Why is it important to have a budget?</h2>
                <p>A well-planned budget transforms uncertainty into informed decisions.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Control expenses:</strong> recording each item reveals gaps where you can save (subscriptions, impulse purchases, mobility).</li>
                    <li><strong>Plan for the future:</strong> Knowing how much is left allows you to decide whether to save for a home, change a car or invest in education.</li>
                    <li><strong>Create a contingency fund:</strong> advisors recommend a minimum of three months of fixed expenses for emergencies such as repairs or loss of employment.</li>
                    <li><strong>Living with greater financial peace of mind:</strong> fewer surprises means more confidence to adapt to changes in canton, family or work.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Official sources</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>HTMLTAG_117___Swiss Budget Advisory Service (Conseil Budgetaire)</a> – real examples of budgets and free advice.</li>
                    <li><a href="https://conseil-budgetaire.ch/individus/budgethilfen/budgetvorlagen" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Budget models</a> ready to download and adapt.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>`
