        featuredImage: "media/guides/medicos-urgencias-suiza.jpg",
        imageAlt: "Reception of an emergency medical center (Permanence Médicale) in Switzerland",
        content: `<div class="article-content">
                <p>Understanding how to navigate the daily practice of Swiss healthcare will save you problems (and financial scares).</p>

                <h2>Choose a doctor according to your insurance model</h2>
                <p>The cheapest LAMal model is usually the "HMO Model" or "Family Doctor". This means that you cannot go directly to a specialist or hospital without first calling a centralized line, or without strictly going through your assigned GP. If you skip this, the insurance may refuse to pay the bill.</p>
                
                <h2>The Emergencies (Urgences / Notfall)</h2>
                <p>Going to a hospital emergency room should be genuinely for serious cases. For quick but non-vital care, the usual thing in Switzerland is to go to the "Permanence Médicale" (Polyclinics), where they treat you quickly in order of arrival at a much lower cost than the hospital.</p>

                <h2>The payment system: The Tiers-garant vs Tiers-payant</h2>
                <p>When you go to the pharmacy or receive a medical bill, you will be faced with two models:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Tiers-guarantee (Direct payment):</strong> The bill arrives at your home (or you pay it at the pharmacy), you pay it out of your pocket, and then you send the QR code or receipt to your insurance. If you have already exceeded your deductible, the insurance will return the money to you.</li>
                    <li><strong>Tiers-payant:</strong> The doctor or pharmacy sends the bill directly to the insurer. The insurer pays it, and if you have not exceeded your deductible, the insurer will issue you an invoice so that you can pay the corresponding amount.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>`
