        imageAlt: "Retired couple enjoying coffee on a terrace overlooking the Swiss Alps",
        content: `<div class="article-content">
                <p>One of the most frequently asked questions is what pension is left after a working life in Switzerland. The system is mainly supported by two pillars (AVS and LPP).</p>
                
                <h2>The Fundamental Pillars</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>1st Pillar (AVS):</strong> State pension. The minimum is around 1,200 CHF and the maximum is 2,450 CHF per month. It depends on the years contributed without interruptions.</li>
                    <li><strong>2nd Pillar (LPP):</strong> Professional pension fund. Capital accumulated during your employment. When you retire you can choose between a monthly income or withdraw the capital.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Examples according to age of arrival</h2>
                <p>Expectations change drastically depending on when you start trading in the country:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Arrival at 30 years old:</strong> Ideal scenario. After 35 years of contributions, it is realistic to aim for a total pension of between 4,000 and 5,500 CHF (AVS + LPP).</li>
                    <li><strong>Arrival at 40 years old:</strong> Time is starting to get tight. The AVS will be partial and the LPP will be smaller. The pension could be around 3,000 - 4,000 CHF.</li>
                    <li><strong>Arrival at 50 years old:</strong> Delicate case. Without very high salaries, the total pension could remain between 2,000 and 3,000 CHF, making additional private savings necessary.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="callout tip">
                    <strong>Note on agreements:</strong> The years worked in Spain are not lost; Each country will pay its proportional part upon reaching retirement age.
                </div>
            </div>`
