<p>It is one of those topics that generates confusion from day one. Technically, Switzerland does not have a minimum wage set at the federal level. But saying that "in Switzerland there is no minimum wage" is simplifying to the point of misinforming, because in practice there are well-defined salary floors, they just work differently from what we know in Spain. 

The main mechanism is collective labor agreements, called CCT (Contrats Collectifs de Travail in French or GAV in German). They are agreements negotiated between unions and employers' associations that set minimum wages by sector. The hospitality industry, construction, commerce, cleaning, watchmaking, the health sector, security... practically all sectors where foreign labor is concentrated have active CCTs. Working below these minimums is illegal, and labor inspections are real and have consequences. 

Added to this is that several cantons have introduced their own cantonal minimum wage by law. Geneva leads with 24.59 francs per hour in 2026, which is equivalent to more than 4,400 gross francs per month full-time. Neuchâtel, Jura, Ticino and Basel-Stadt also have their own minimums. When you are going to negotiate a salary or evaluate an offer, the first thing you should check is if there is a CCT applicable to your sector in the canton where you are going to work. That figure is your real reference, not what they want to offer you.</p> 
